column74: The UK is removing all countries from its red travel list, just weeks after reactivating the list in response to the new Omicron variant.    As of tomorrow, 15 December, people arriving from 11 African countries will no longer need to stay in one of the government-run quarantine hotels.    People currently in a UK quarantine hotel will also be allowed to leave early, as long as they do not test positive for COVID-19.    However all current testing requirements will remain in place, Transport Secretary Grant Shapps confirmed on Twitter this afternoon.    he UK recently updated its travel rules, stipulating that all arrivals must now show a negative pre-departure PCR or lateral flow test that was taken within 48 hours of arriving.    This is in addition to a day 2 PCR test, which both UK citizens and visitors must await the results of in isolation. The rules vary for unvaccinated travellers.    http://web.archive.org/web/20211215095343/https://www.euronews.com/travel/2021/12/14/uk-travel-all-countries-removed-from-the-uk-s-red-quarantine-list

column79: The government has quietly introduced a loophole to its eviction ban that waters down protections for people who lost their jobs during the pandemic.    Ministers on Friday announced that they were extending the ban on bailiff evictions that has been in place since the first lockdown in March, covering most tenants for another six weeks. column115: Still protections in place so coded as a 2.    Hundreds of thousands of care home residents will be able to leave the buildings where they have been confined for more than a year without having to self-isolate on their return.    They will be allowed out for visits to gardens, parks and beaches from Tuesday without being forced to self-isolate upon their return.    The latest move to relax the restrictions on the estimated 420,000 people living in English care homes was announced as coronavirus rates continue to fall across the country. Almost 95 per cent of residents have received their first dose of the vaccine, while 71 per cent have been jabbed twice.    They remain forbidden for the moment to go out in groups or to meet more than one person at a time outdoors, although this restriction could be further loosened later this month.    Visits indoors, apart from to use toilet facilities, remain banned and people are urged to avoid taking public transport if possible. An exemption will be made for people who want to vote in person in next Thursdays local elections.    https://web.archive.org/web/20210507094208/https://inews.co.uk/news/uk/freedom-thousands-elderly-care-home-residents-from-tuesday-visits-outside-restored-981020

column69: People living in 8 areas with high cases of the Indian Variant are recommended to reduce movement    If youre in an area where the new COVID-19 variant is spreading  This new variant is sometimes referred to as the variant first identified in India. It is spreading fastest in:    Bedford Borough Council  Blackburn with Darwen Borough Council  Bolton Metropolitan Borough Council  Burnley Borough Council  Kirklees Council  Leicester City Council  London Borough of Hounslow  North Tyneside Council  The new COVID-19 variant spreads more easily from person to person. To help stop the spread, you should take particular caution when meeting anyone outside your household or support bubble.    In the areas listed above, wherever possible, you should try to:    meet outside rather than inside where possible  keep 2 metres apart from people that you dont live with (unless you have formed a support bubble with them), this includes friends and family you dont live with  minimise travel in and out of affected areas    https://web.archive.org/web/20210528115758/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/covid-19-coronavirus-restrictions-what-you-can-and-cannot-do    https://web.archive.org/web/20210528115831/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-57232728    Controversy over the way this was communicated:    "We woke up on Monday morning to find apparently that guidance had been in force on the government's website since Friday, telling us not to move in and out of affected areas but nobody had bothered to tell us," she said. column74: Changes to UK International arrivals lists on 5 Aug:    The UK government has today (5 August 2021) announced that arrivals from France to England will no longer need to quarantine if they are fully vaccinated.    The step aligns France with the rest of the amber list now that the proportion of beta variant cases has fallen, where those who are fully vaccinated with a vaccine authorised and administered in the UK, US or Europe do not need to quarantine when arriving in England.    This move also simplifies the system to 3 categories, as well as the green watchlist to give travellers notice where green status is at risk.    arrivals from France will no longer need to quarantine if they are fully vaccinated  Austria, Germany, Slovenia, Slovakia, Latvia, Romania and Norway to be added to the governments green list for travel  India, Bahrain, Qatar and the United Arab Emirates (UAE) will also be moved from the red to the amber list  Georgia, Mexico, La Reunion and Mayotte added to the red list to safeguard domestic vaccine rollout    https://web.archive.org/web/20210806111415/https://www.gov.uk/government/news/international-travel-country-listings-update

column74: The UK is removing all countries from its red travel list, just weeks after reactivating the list in response to the new Omicron variant.    As of tomorrow, 15 December, people arriving from 11 African countries will no longer need to stay in one of the government-run quarantine hotels.    People currently in a UK quarantine hotel will also be allowed to leave early, as long as they do not test positive for COVID-19.    However all current testing requirements will remain in place, Transport Secretary Grant Shapps confirmed on Twitter this afternoon.    he UK recently updated its travel rules, stipulating that all arrivals must now show a negative pre-departure PCR or lateral flow test that was taken within 48 hours of arriving.    This is in addition to a day 2 PCR test, which both UK citizens and visitors must await the results of in isolation. The rules vary for unvaccinated travellers.    http://web.archive.org/web/20211215095343/https://www.euronews.com/travel/2021/12/14/uk-travel-all-countries-removed-from-the-uk-s-red-quarantine-list

column33: Domestic certificates were introduced on 29 November 2021 and will be enforceable from 13 December 2021.    Why you need a domestic certificate  Domestic certificates were introduced on 29 November and will be enforceable on 13 December 2021. This means that some hospitality venues will ask for evidence of your vaccination status.    Venues include:    nightclubs  hospitality venues which serve food and drink  cinemas, theatres, concert halls and conference centres  indoor events with 500 or more attendees with some or all of the audience not normally seated  outdoor events with 4,000 or more attendees with some or all of the audience not normally seated  events where more than 10,000 people will be present, regardless of whether they are seated    http://web.archive.org/web/20211215101228/https://www.nidirect.gov.uk/services/apply-domestic-covid-vaccination-certificate

column74: The UK is removing all countries from its red travel list, just weeks after reactivating the list in response to the new Omicron variant.    As of tomorrow, 15 December, people arriving from 11 African countries will no longer need to stay in one of the government-run quarantine hotels.    People currently in a UK quarantine hotel will also be allowed to leave early, as long as they do not test positive for COVID-19.    However all current testing requirements will remain in place, Transport Secretary Grant Shapps confirmed on Twitter this afternoon.    he UK recently updated its travel rules, stipulating that all arrivals must now show a negative pre-departure PCR or lateral flow test that was taken within 48 hours of arriving.    This is in addition to a day 2 PCR test, which both UK citizens and visitors must await the results of in isolation. The rules vary for unvaccinated travellers.    http://web.archive.org/web/20211215095343/https://www.euronews.com/travel/2021/12/14/uk-travel-all-countries-removed-from-the-uk-s-red-quarantine-list

column60: Scots are to be ordered to stay at home amid a fresh Covid-19 lockdown on 5 January. These are the toughest restrictions Scotland has faced since the lockdown of March 2020.      The new rules - which will be put down in law - mean Scots will only be allowed to leave home for essential purposes, such as shopping for food and medicine, exercise and caring responsibilities.    No limit is to be put on how many times people can go out to exercise, but outdoor meetings are to be limited to a maximum of two people from two households.      These rules will apply across the Scottish mainland until at least the end of January, and will be kept under review.    https://web.archive.org/web/20210104154939/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-55531069

column24: New lockdown rules:    1. Click and collect  The availability and operation of click and collect services will be limited to retailers selling essential items such as clothes, footwear, baby equipment, homeware and books. Also, outlets that sell electrical goods; do key cutting; undertake shoe repairs, plus garden centres and plant nurseries can continue the collect service.    For qualifying businesses, staggered appointments will need to be offered to avoid any potential for queuing, and access inside premises for collection will not be permitted.    Analysis: Business clicks but doesnt collect  2. Takeaway services  Customers in Scotland will no longer be allowed to go inside to collect takeaway food or coffee. Businesses will have to operate from a serving hatch or doorway.    The aim is to reduce the risk of customers coming into contact indoors with each other, or with staff.    3. Alcohol consumption  It will be against the law in all level four areas of Scotland to drink alcohol outdoors in public.    This will mean that buying a takeaway pint and consuming on the street will not be permitted.    It is intended to underline the message that people should only be leaving home for essential purposes.      https://web.archive.org/web/20210115173223/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-55649853
column60: The Scottish government is strengthening the obligation on employers to allow their staff to work from home whenever possible. column74: The UK is removing all countries from its red travel list, just weeks after reactivating the list in response to the new Omicron variant.    As of tomorrow, 15 December, people arriving from 11 African countries will no longer need to stay in one of the government-run quarantine hotels.    People currently in a UK quarantine hotel will also be allowed to leave early, as long as they do not test positive for COVID-19.    However all current testing requirements will remain in place, Transport Secretary Grant Shapps confirmed on Twitter this afternoon.    he UK recently updated its travel rules, stipulating that all arrivals must now show a negative pre-departure PCR or lateral flow test that was taken within 48 hours of arriving.    This is in addition to a day 2 PCR test, which both UK citizens and visitors must await the results of in isolation. The rules vary for unvaccinated travellers.    http://web.archive.org/web/20211215095343/https://www.euronews.com/travel/2021/12/14/uk-travel-all-countries-removed-from-the-uk-s-red-quarantine-list

from 27 December 2021, mandatory table service was reintroduced to venues serving alcohol for consumption on their premises  this means that you must be seated to consume any food or alcohol in a place that serves alcohol. column115: Some restrictions still in place in elderly care homes following 7 August but much less stringent than previous policy.    Version 10 of the guidance supersedes previous versions. The key changes are:    To introduce essential visitors. Each resident can now nominate an essential visitor. The essential visitor may visit the resident regularly indoors during a COVID-19 outbreak at the care home provided the resident or visitor do not themselves have COVID-19 (unless there are exceptional circumstances). This will ensure that people can continue to benefit from regular visits by a nominated essential visitor when wider restrictions on routine visits maybe in place.      To remove the limit of two indoor visitors at the same time per resident. This will now be subject to a risk assessment by the care home.  To remove the need for visitors to wear face coverings in outdoor areas of the care home.   To amend requirements on use of face coverings in indoor areas.   To clarify that indoor visits can take place in residents rooms as well as in a designated visiting space.    https://web.archive.org/web/20210811111305/https://gov.wales/visits-care-homes-guidance-providers-html

column24: People in Wales now need an NHS Covid pass to legally enter nightclubs and large events.    Anyone aged over 18 will be required to show the pass to prove they are either fully vaccinated or have had a negative lateral flow test result within the last 48 hours.    The new rule came into effect on 11 October.    https://web.archive.org/web/20211011105950/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-wales-politics-58600373

column74: The UK is removing all countries from its red travel list, just weeks after reactivating the list in response to the new Omicron variant.    As of tomorrow, 15 December, people arriving from 11 African countries will no longer need to stay in one of the government-run quarantine hotels.    People currently in a UK quarantine hotel will also be allowed to leave early, as long as they do not test positive for COVID-19.    However all current testing requirements will remain in place, Transport Secretary Grant Shapps confirmed on Twitter this afternoon.    he UK recently updated its travel rules, stipulating that all arrivals must now show a negative pre-departure PCR or lateral flow test that was taken within 48 hours of arriving.    This is in addition to a day 2 PCR test, which both UK citizens and visitors must await the results of in isolation. The rules vary for unvaccinated travellers.    http://web.archive.org/web/20211215095343/https://www.euronews.com/travel/2021/12/14/uk-travel-all-countries-removed-from-the-uk-s-red-quarantine-list

column24: Wales at Level 2 from 26 December 2021    Groups of no more than six people will be allowed to meet in pubs, cinemas and restaurants in Wales from 26 December, when the two metre social distancing rule will also return to public places and offices.    Measures will be put in place to protect customers and staff, such as one-way systems and barriers.    Fans will be banned from all sporting events in Wales from 26 December.    Nightclubs, originally planned to close on 27 December, will now shut a day earlier.    Face masks are still required in most public places, including buses, shops and hospitals.    http://web.archive.org/web/20220110171738/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-wales-55333756
